Use of the Internet and social networks by the government of Ecuador is
rapidly increasing. Is this an attempt to increase government transparency, a
new media strategy or alternatively, is this the government's way of bypassing
the media silence?

Based at the International Centre of Higher Studies in Communication for Latin
America [(@ciespal)](http://twitter.com/ciespal "CIESPAL") [es], Alexandra
Ayala is carrying out
[research](http://www.enlaceecuador.com/noticias/politica/4205-ciespal-
presidencia-de-la-republica-tiene-sistema-integral-de-comunicacion.html) [es]
into the online presence of the Ecuadorian President [Rafael
Correa](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rafael_Correa).

> El portal oficial de la Presidencia de la República
> (www.presidencia.gob.ec), es multimedia e interactivo, permiten a sus
> visitantes enlaces directos con una serie de canales y redes sociales como:
> El Ciudadano, periódico digital oficial del Gobierno; facebook; twitter;
> youtube; vimeo; flickr; livestream; canal de distribución de audios; canal
> de distribución de PDF; canal de distribución de power point; sitio
> streaming en vivo; ministerios, entre otros

The official website for the Presidency of Ecuador
([www.presidencia.gob.ec](http://www.presidencia.gob.ec/)) is full of
multimedia content and it is interactive. It also contains a number of
hyperlinks that allow visitors to access a series of associated websites and
social network accounts such as [El
Ciudadano](http://www.elciudadano.gov.ec/),the official online newspaper for
the Government of Ecuador, Facebook;
[Twitter](http://twitter.com/presidencia_ec);
[YouTube](http://www.youtube.com/profile?user=presidenciaecuador), Vimeo,
Flickr, Livestream as well as a range of websites for sharing audio clips, PDF
files and Powerpoint files. Similarly, there is also a link to a live video
streaming website as well as links to the website for government departments

The International Centre of Higher Studies in Communication for Latin America
has [posted](http://twitter.com/ciespal/status/2052365108641792) [es] various
[tweets](http://twitter.com/ciespal/status/2050451331612672) [es] in relation
to their findings:

> [#ciberactivismo](http://twitter.com/search?q=%23ciberactivismo
> "#ciberactivismo") El monitoreo arroja como resultado que la actividad del
> presidente en redes sociales es alta[
> ](http://twitter.com/ciespal/status/2052365108641792)

[#ciberactivismo](http://twitter.com/search?q=%23ciberactivismo
"#ciberactivismo") (cyberactivism): This research has arisen as a result of
the ever increasing online presence of the President of Ecuador on social
networks[ ](http://twitter.com/ciespal/status/2052365108641792)

> [#ciberactivismo](http://twitter.com/search?q=%23ciberactivismo
> "#ciberactivismo") Rafael Correa fue el primer presidente latinoamericano
> que tuvo un blog. Eso se le reconoce a internacionalmente

[#ciberactivismo](http://twitter.com/search?q=%23ciberactivismo
"#ciberactivismo") (cyberactivism): The President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa
was the first Latin American president to have his own blog. This is
acknowledged across the world

The [Facebook](http://www.facebook.com/PresidenciaEcuador) [es] page,
“Presidencia de la República de Ecuador” (the Presidency of Ecuador) has more
than 9000 fans and the Twitter account, “Presidencia de Ecuador”
([@Presidencia_Ec](http://twitter.com/Presidencia_Ec/followers)) [es], has
27,866[ ](http://twitter.com/Presidencia_Ec/followers "Mira quién sigue a
Presidencia_Ec")followers.

> [![](https://es.globalvoicesonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/Screen-
> shot-2010-11-11-at-12.07.27-PM-1024x800.png)](https://es.globalvoicesonline.org/wp-
> content/uploads/2010/11/Screen-shot-2010-11-11-at-12.07.27-PM.png)  
>

Discussing national politics on social networks is not a new phenomenon,
however the online presence of the Government of Ecuador is somewhat unique.
Referring to a [police strike
](https://globalvoicesonline.org/2010/09/30/ecuador-police-strike-denounced-
as-attempt-to-destabilize-country/)that took place on September 30, Edward
Gonzalez [ ](http://twitter.com/eduu90 "Edward Gonzalez") writes,

> EN ECUADOR el lider de la policia nacional y el presidente ya no son
> amigos.. por lo menos eso dice sus cuentas en facebook jiji..

The chief of the national police of Ecuador and the president are no longer
friends…at least that's what their Facebook accounts show hahaha

This is not a small issue neither. Five years ago, Ecuadorians were talking
about the ineffeciency displayed by their government, the political processes
and the judiciary in addressing the issues of the internet and the use of new
technologies by those in the Andean subregion.

As the online newspaper _Juventud Rebelde_
[highlighted](http://www.juventudrebelde.cu/internacionales/2010-09-30/facebook-
un-arma-contra-el-golpe-en-ecuador/) [es],

> [Facebook](http://www.facebook.com/) ha devenido una vía de información y de
> movilización alternativa, donde los simpatizantes del presidente ecuatoriano
> suben videos y fotos, enlaces con publicaciones de diarios y televisoras y
> comentan la situación del país en el grupo El grupo llamado «No al golpe de
> Estado en Ecuador».

[](http://www.facebook.com/)[](http://www.facebook.com/)[Facebook](http://www.facebook.com/)
has become an alternative means to sharing information and the social network
facilitates gatherings in which supporters of the President of Ecuador can
upload videos and photos as well as post links to newspaper articles and
television broadcasts. Supporters can also discuss Ecuador's position by
posting on the Facebook group, “No al golpe de Estado en Ecuador” (Opposition
to a coup d'etat in Ecuador).

On Facebook, “[Marcha por la decencia
nacional](http://www.facebook.com/pages/Marcha-por-la-decencia-
nacional/145143125528943?v=wall)” [es] (March for national decency) and
“[Verde Esperanza”](http://www.facebook.com/pages/Verde-
Esperanza/119630374759856) __ [es] (Green Hope) are online initiatives taking
place on social networks in Ecuador in support of President Correa.

_[ALT1040](http://alt1040.com/2007/04/presidencia-de-ecuador-pone-su-canal-en-
youtube)_ [es] tries to explain the use of social networks by the government
of Ecuador due to a backdrop of opposition from the national media.

> En mi último viaje a Ecuador noté como algunas acciones hechas por el
> presidente Rafael Correa están siendo extrañamente ignoradas por los medios
> masivos ecuatorianos, mi ejemplo favorito es el pago de la deuda al Fondo
> Monetario Internacional, una gran y positiva noticia que casualmente no
> aparece en ningún lado de la página principal de [El
> Universo](http://eluniverso.com/), supuestamente el diario más serio de ese
> país, aunque sí tienen un artículo al respecto, pero que es sumamente
> pequeño y una simple reproducción de un cable de Reuters;

During my last trip to Ecuador, I couldn't help but notice how the larger
media corporations failed to cover any stories that involved the president of
the country, President Rafael Correa. My favourite example of this has to be
the big story when Ecuador was repaying its debts to the International
Monetary Fund and yet on the front pages of [El
Universo](http://eluniverso.com/) [es], allegedly one of the most
‘professional’ newspapers in Ecuador, there was no mention of this story and
you had to flick through to one of the inside pages to find a tiny article
about this which seemed to just be a direct lift of what Reuters had reported.

Other countries are also realising the importance of social networking in
Ecuador and several other accounts are now popping up covering the affairs of
the country – accounts such as those belonging to [Centro Knight
UT](http://twitter.com/centroknightut/status/26097828341) [es]
([@centroknightut](http://twitter.com/centroknightut "Centro Knight UT")),
Gerardo Albarrán
([@saladeprensa](http://twitter.com/#!/saladeprensa/status/26405701380)) [es],
[@twitvenezuela](http://twitter.com/twitvenezuela "twitvenezuela") [es] as
well as other [Twitter
accounts](http://twitter.com/twitvenezuela/status/26005778064) [es] that
tweeted about the police strike on September 30 in Ecuador.

The reliance upon social networks and the Internet has opened up other
opportunities. On one occasion, the official website of the Presidency of
Ecuador was hacked and forced offline.
[_LaPatilla_](http://www.lapatilla.com/site/2010/10/01/el-facebook-del-
presidente-correa-muestra-su-lado-sexy/) [es] covered this story underlining
how this incident resulted in the “sexy” side of the President being shown.

> El presidente de Ecuador, Rafael Correa, también tiene su Facebook. En él se
> retratan varias de sus facetas durante su mandato en ese país. Allí Correa
> muestra su lado más “pícaro y sexy”, además de sus habilidades musicales…

The president of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, also has a Facebook account. This
account highlights various sides to him and his time in office. President
Correa appears to show his “cheeky and sexy” side on Facebook as well as his
musical talents…”

_B10,_ an online portal for discussing what's happening in Ecuador, posted an
article relating to the [Facebook](http://www.b10.com.ec/2010/10/13/facebook-
describe-el-30s-de-lucio/) [es] account belonging to the former President of
Ecuador, and the man President Correa
[blamed](http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-11447519) for the
police uprising of September 30, [Lucio
Gutiérrez](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucio_Gutierrez). This illustrates
that social networks, politics and information can all come together in one
place resulting in transparency and the involvement of the public.

